What is a JOIN?
// important concept

JOIN is used when data is stored in more than one table and we want to see it together.

ðŸ“Œ Example

EMP table â†’ employee details

DEPT table â†’ department details

To see employee name + department name, we must JOIN the tables.

Important Rule (Very Easy)

ðŸ‘‰ If you join n tables, you need n âˆ’ 1 join conditions.

Tables	Join Conditions
2 tables	1 condition
3 tables	2 conditions
EQUI JOIN

ðŸ”¹ Meaning: Join using =` (equal to) operator
ðŸ”¹ Columns must have same datatype
ðŸ”¹ Returns only matching rows

Example (Old Oracle style â€“ 8i)
SELECT e.ename, d.dname
FROM emp e, dept d
WHERE e.deptno = d.deptno;


âœ” Shows employees only if deptno matches
âŒ If deptno = 40 exists only in DEPT, it will not show

INNER JOIN

ðŸ”¹ Works same as EQUI JOIN
ðŸ”¹ Returns only matching rows
ðŸ”¹ Uses ANSI syntax (Oracle 9i+)
ðŸ”¹ Better readability and performance

Example
SELECT e.ename, d.dname
FROM emp e
INNER JOIN dept d
ON e.deptno = d.deptno;


ðŸ“Œ Result is SAME as Equi Join

Important Note (Interview Point â­)

âœ… Equi Join = Inner Join
Only difference is syntax, not result.

8i Joins (NON-ANSI Joins)

ðŸ”¹ Old Oracle syntax
ðŸ”¹ Join condition written in WHERE clause

Syntax
SELECT col1, col2
FROM table1, table2
WHERE table1.common_col = table2.common_col;


ðŸ“Œ Example

SELECT e.ename, d.dname
FROM emp e, dept d
WHERE e.deptno = d.deptno;

9i Joins (ANSI Joins)

ðŸ”¹ New and recommended syntax
ðŸ”¹ Join condition written using JOIN â€¦ ON

Syntax
SELECT col1, col2
FROM table1
JOIN table2
ON table1.common_col = table2.common_col;


ðŸ“Œ Example

SELECT e.ename, d.dname
FROM emp e
JOIN dept d
ON e.deptno = d.deptno;

Using Table Aliases (Very Important ðŸ‘)

ðŸ”¹ Alias = short name for table
ðŸ”¹ Improves performance & readability
ðŸ”¹ Must use alias in SELECT and ON

Example
SELECT e.ename, d.dname
FROM emp e
JOIN dept d
ON e.deptno = d.deptno;


âœ” e â†’ emp
âœ” d â†’ dept

Simple One-Line Summary

JOIN â†’ combine tables

Equi Join â†’ = operator, old style

Inner Join â†’ same result, new style

8i Join â†’ WHERE clause

9i Join â†’ JOIN â€¦ ON

Aliases â†’ faster, cleaner queries

